  "prompt": "Why did Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) fail?",
  "response": "Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) failed due to several key factors:\n\n1. Missed the Personal Computer Revolution\n- Failed to recognize the potential of personal computers early on\n- Slow to develop competitive PC products\n- Focused on minicomputers while market was shifting\n\n2. Technological Shifts\n- The rise of microprocessor-based systems\n- Inability to quickly adapt to client-server computing model\n- Slower innovation compared to emerging competitors like Sun Microsystems\n\n3. Strategic Management Issues\n- Bureaucratic corporate culture\n- Slow decision-making processes\n- Resistance to changing business models\n- Reluctance to abandon traditional product lines\n\n4. Competitive Pressures\n- Intense competition from IBM, Sun Microsystems, and emerging PC manufacturers\n- Declining profit margins in minicomputer market\n- Inability to compete effectively on price and performance\n\n5. Financial Challenges\n- Declining market share\n- High operating costs\n- Reduced research and development investments\n\n6. Leadership Challenges\n- Ken Olsen's conservative management style\n- Difficulty transitioning from founder-led to more adaptive leadership\n\nUltimately, DEC was acquired by Compaq in 1998, marking the end of the once-pioneering computer company. The company's failure was primarily due to its inability to adapt quickly to rapidly changing technology and market dynamics.",
